  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "l1ZKLcgssevuSGaUgehxoACZ9cM=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "Swarm /bytes chunks are content-addressed: the reference is derived from the chunk's content (BMT hash). Two consequences for duplication analysis:\n\n**1. Same data -> same reference, regardless of uploader.** If Alice and Bob both upload the same encrypted operation batch, they produce identical chunk references. The network stores it once.\n\n**2. Immutability is intrinsic.** Once written, a chunk cannot change \u2014 changing the content would change the reference. This is why /bytes is durable until stamp expiration and why \"versioning\" requires feeds (mutable pointers) layered on top.\n\n**Implications for our duplication picture**:\n- Our encrypted operation batches are per-user (encryption key differs), so cross-user de-dup is limited in practice.\n- But within a user's own writes, re-uploading the same batch (e.g., after a retry) is effectively free \u2014 the network already has the chunk.\n- This is different from PostgreSQL/IndexedDB where \"duplicate\" means \"both rows exist and take up bytes twice.\"\n\n**Terminology care**: when the analysis says \"operations exist in both PGlite and Swarm,\" the Swarm side is the content-addressed chunk \u2014 a single chunk even if uploaded many times. PGlite, by contrast, stores raw rows with no content-addressing.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
    }
  },
